Predicting Stock Price Movement Using Machine Learning¶

Problem Statement¶

Analyzing and predicting stock price movement have been a challenging but intriguing task for many analysts and researchers. A model that effectively predicts the direction of future stock price movement will aid investors and traders in making more profitable investments and being better at managing the risks of their portfolios.

Project Overview¶

In this project, several machine learning models, including Random Forest, Gate Recurrent Unit(GRU) and Long Short Term Memory neuro network (LSTM), were adopted to build a classification model that predicts the direction of stock price movement(up or down). The model results were evaluated against the benchmark, Naive Method, using the accuracy metric. This notebook includes the following sections:

  • Data Import
  • Exploritory Data Analysis and Feature Engineering
  • Data Preprocessing
  • Machine Learning and Model Evaluation
  • Results and Conclusion

Data Import¶

The stock price data used in this project is retrieved from Yahoo! Finance via yahoofinancials API. The data consists of trading date(date), opening price(open), highest and lowest price traded in the day(high/low), closing price adjusted for stock splits(close), closing price adjusted for splits and dividends(adjclose), and finally the trading volume(volume). Past 10 years' data of 10 well-known US stocks were used for exploratory data analysis and machine learning.

# Define a functon to retrieve daily historical price data using yahoofinancials API
def getPriceData(symbols, startDate, endDate):
    yf_symbols = YahooFinancials(symbols)
    daily_prices = yf_symbols.get_historical_price_data(startDate, endDate, 'daily')
    return daily_prices

The daily adjusted close prices of most of the stocks show an upward trend over the last 10 years. Such data may not be suitable inputs for Machine Learning models that cannot handle non-stationary data well. In fact, it is more interesting to know whether the stock price will move up or down and by what percentage rather than look at the absolute price. Let's generate the daily return for all the selected stocks. Logarithmic return, which is commonly used in financial data modelling, is used in this project.

In [9]:
# Define a function to generate the log return over a given period:
def genLogReturn(df, period=1):
    '''
    Parameters
    ----------
    df: dataframe
        An intput dataframe of stock price data
    period: int, default to 1
        The number of days over which the log return is calculated
    Returns
    ----------
    dataframe
        The input dataframe with daily log return and trend metrics concatenated
    '''
    df[f'{period}d_return'] = np.log(df['adjclose']) - np.log(df['adjclose'].shift(period))
    df[f'{period}d_future_return'] = df[f'{period}d_return'].shift(-period)
    
    # Storp Price Trend metrics: 1 for moving up, 0 for moving down
    df[f'{period}d_trend'] = [1 if df[f'{period}d_return'][i] > 0 else 0 for i in range(len(df))]
    df[f'{period}d_future_trend'] = [1 if df[f'{period}d_future_return'][i] > 0 else 0 for i in range(len(df))]
    return df

Creating More Features¶

This section generates some technical indicators as additional features for the dataset. To satisfy stationarity, features in price terms are normalized against the adjclose price.

# Define a function to create technical indicators as additional features
def genTechIndicators(df, periods):
    '''
    Parameters
    ----------
    df: dataframe
        An intput dataframe of stock price data
    periods: list
        A list of numbers in days over which the technical indicators will be calculated
    Return
    ----------
    dataframe
        The input dataframe with various technical indicators concatinated
    '''
    # create technical indicators for each period:
    for n in periods:
        # Exponentially Weighted Moving Average divided by adjclose
        df[str(n) + 'd_ma'] = ta.ema(df['adjclose'], length=n) / df['adjclose']

        # Relative Strength Index (RSI)
        df[str(n) + 'd_rsi'] = ta.rsi(df['adjclose'], length=n)
    
    # MACD and Signal Line divided by adjclose
    df['macd'] = ta.macd(df['adjclose'])['MACD_12_26_9'] / df['adjclose']
    df['signal'] = ta.macd(df['adjclose'])['MACDs_12_26_9'] / df['adjclose']

    return df

Define Feature Names and Target Name¶

In this project, two sets of features will be examined depending on individual model's requirements. As a Random Forest model requires 2-Dimentional inputs, in order to use time series/sequence data for prediciton, the number of features has to be one so that the sequence data in each training sample can be reshaped into 2D and be used as a valid input to the RF model. Recurrent Neural Networks(RNN) take 3-Dimentional inputs, and thus can use multiple features for training.

As high, low, open, close and adjclose are highly correlated and all show an upward trend, they will not be used as features.

The first feature set only contains the 1d_return data, to be used for single/multiple-timestep RF and RNN models.

The second feature set includes 1d_return, volume and all technical indicators created above, to be used for single-timestep RF and RNN models.

The target for prediction is the direction of stock price movement for the next day, i.e. the 1d_future_trend.

Data Preprocessing for Machine Learning¶

This section prepares the unscaled train/test datasets. The scaling of the data will be done in the subsequent RNN section.

In [29]:
# Define a function to prepare training and testing datasets
def dataPrep(df, feature_names, target_name, split_pct=0.8):
    '''
    Parameteres
    ----------
    df: dataframe
        Input dataframe to be split into train/test features/target
    feature_names: list
        feature names
    target_name: list
        target name
    split_pct: float, default to 0.8
        ratio to split train/test data
    Return
    ----------
    dataframe, dataframe, dataframe, dataframe
        train_features, train_targets, test_features, test_targets
    '''
    # Drop NA values
    df = df.dropna()

    # Create features and targets
    features = df[feature_names]
    targets = df[target_name]
    
    # Create train, test splits
    train_size = int(df.shape[0] * split_pct)

    # Exclude the last day in the training dataset as its '1d_future_trend' is unkown within the training dataset itself
    train_features = features[:train_size-1]
    train_targets = targets[:train_size-1]

    test_features = features[train_size:]
    test_targets = targets[train_size:]

    print(f'Train size: {train_features.shape}\nTest size: {test_features.shape}')
    return train_features, train_targets, test_features, test_targets

# Define a generic function that can run the prediction and calculate model eval metrics
def getModelResults(model, eval_metric, x_train, y_train, x_test, y_test, v=False):
    '''
    Parameters
    ----------
    model: model
        a fitted machine learning model
    eval_metric: str
        name of model evaluation metric
    x_train, y_train, x_test, y_test: dataframe/ndarray
        train_features, train_targets, test_features, test_targets
    v: bool, default to False
        verbose mode for printing extra info about train/test prediction results
    Return
    ----------
    ndarray, ndarray, flat, float
        train_preds, test_preds, metric_train, metric_test
    '''
    train_preds = model.predict(x_train)
    test_preds = model.predict(x_test)

    if v == True:
        print(train_preds.shape, test_preds.shape)
    
    if eval_metric == 'accuracy':
        metric_train = accuracy_score(y_train, train_preds)
        metric_test = accuracy_score(y_test, test_preds)
    else:
        print('Unsupported eval metric.')

    return train_preds, test_preds, metric_train, metric_test

Random Forest Hyperparameter Tuning¶

Initial hyperparameter ranges tried:

  • n_estimators: list(range(100,501,100))
  • max_depth: list(range(5,31,5))
  • min_samples_splits: list(range(2,7,1))
  • min_samples_leaf: list(range(1,4,1))
  • max_features: ['sqrt', 'log2', None],
  • criterion: ['gini', 'entropy', 'log_loss']
  • bootstrap: [True, False]

Observations:

  • Increasing the number of estimators, min_sample_splits and min_samples_leaf did not significantly improve model performance.
  • Larger max_depth tends to overfit -- giving high accuracy for the training dataset but low accuracy for test dataset. Training accuracy reached > 90% with 9+ max depths, while test accuracy stayed between 48% to 54%.
  • No restriction on max_features yielded slightly higher accuracy than with restriction. Max_features was removed from hyperparameter tuning below as its default setting is None.
  • Gini is used as the criterion for training since it slightly outperformed the other two.
  • Bootstrap performed better than no boostrap. Bootstrap is not included in the hyperparameters dict below as its default setting is True.

After a few iterations, below hyperparameter ranges are chosen to demonstrate hyperparameter tuning.

Random Forest with Past Sequence Data¶

Now let's look at using past sequences in a Random Forest classifer for prediction using 1d_return as the only feature, as discussed earlier. This feature will be reshaped into an array containing past n-day data.

In [43]:
# Define a function to prepare train/test data with past sequence data
def sequenceDataPrepRfr(train_feature, train_target, test_feature, test_target, timestep):
    '''
    Parameters
    ----------
    train_feature/test_feature:
        '1d_return'
    train_target/test_target:
        '1d_day_future_return'
    timestep: int
        timesteps in days
    Return
    ----------
    ndarray, ndarray, ndarray, ndarray
        train_features, train_targets, test_features, test_targets
    '''
    # The n-timestep sequence data includes the data of the current day, as the prediction target is 1d_future_trend.
    x_train = np.array([train_feature[i-timestep:i] for i in range(timestep, len(train_feature)+1)])
    y_train = np.array([train_target.iloc[i-1] for i in range(timestep, len(train_feature)+1)])
    y_train = np.reshape(y_train, (y_train.shape[0], 1))
    x_test = np.array([test_feature[i-timestep:i] for i in range(timestep, len(test_feature)+1)])
    y_test = np.array([test_target.iloc[i-1] for i in range(timestep, len(test_feature)+1)])
    y_test = np.reshape(y_test, (y_test.shape[0], 1))
    
    return x_train, y_train, x_test, y_test

Random Forest model's 2-day prediction test accuracy is comparable to the benchmark model's, althought the train accuracy is 10% higher. Let's now examine how models that work with both past sequence data and multiple features perform.

Recurrent Neural Networks¶

A recurrent neural network (RNN) is a type of artificial neural network that deals with sequential data or time series data. In the following sections, two types of RNNs, namely GRU and LSTM, will be explored and examined. The training data fed into a RNN model needs to be in the shape of NxTxD, where:

  • N is the number of samples
  • T is the number of timesteps (in days in this project)
  • D is the number of features

Besides, as the values of some of the features, such as 1d_return, are small, standardization will be applied for more efficient model training.

RNN Data Preprocessing¶

In [46]:
# Define a function to standardize the training and test data
def standardizeData(train_features, test_features, scaler=StandardScaler()):
    scaler.fit(train_features)
    scaled_train_features = scaler.transform(train_features)
    scaled_test_features = scaler.transform(test_features)
    return scaled_train_features, scaled_test_features

# Define a function to prepare the features and targets data for a given timestep
def dataPrepRnn(train_features, train_target, test_features, test_target, timestep):
    x_train = []
    y_train = []
    x_test = []
    y_test = []
    
    # The n-timestep sequence data includes the data of the current day, as the prediction target is 1d_future_trend.
    x_train = np.array([train_features[i-timestep:i, :] for i in range(timestep, len(train_features)+1)])
    y_train = np.array([train_target.iloc[i-1] for i in range(timestep, len(train_target)+1)])
    x_test = np.array([test_features[i-timestep:i, :] for i in range(timestep, len(test_features)+1)])
    y_test = np.array([test_target.iloc[i-1] for i in range(timestep, len(test_target)+1)])

    return np.reshape(x_train, (-1, timestep, train_features.shape[1])), y_train, np.reshape(x_test, (-1, timestep, test_features.shape[1])), y_test

Gated Recurrent Unit¶

Gated Recurrent Unit (GRU) is a type of RNN which is controlled by "gates" that determine the weights of the past and new information. Let's start with using 1 feature for model training.

In [53]:
# Define a function to build a GRU Model
def buildGruModel(dataShape):
    '''
    Parameters
    ----------
    dataShape: list
        the shape parameter of the training input
    Return
    ----------
    GRU model
    '''
    N = dataShape[0]        # number of samples
    T = dataShape[1]        # timesteps
    D = dataShape[2]        # feature dimention
    K = 1                   # number of outputs

    model = Sequential()
    model.add(GRU(50, return_sequences=True, input_shape=(T, D)))
    model.add(Dropout(0.2))
    model.add(GRU(50, return_sequences=False))
    model.add(Dropout(0.2))
    model.add(Dense(K, activation='sigmoid' ))

    # Complie the model
    model.compile(optimizer='adam', loss='binary_crossentropy', metrics=['accuracy'])
    return model

# Define a function to plot RNN training loss and accuracy
def plotRnnResults(history, title=None):
    fig, ax1 = plt.subplots(figsize=(4, 4))
    ax2 = ax1.twinx()
    ax1.plot(history.history['loss'], 'b-', alpha=0.8)
    ax2.plot(history.history['accuracy'], 'g', alpha=0.8)

    ax1.set_ylabel('loss', color='b')
    ax2.set_ylabel('accuracy', color='g')
    
    if title:
        plt.title(title)
    plt.show();

GRU with More Features¶

Hyperparameter turning has been done but not shown in this notebook, details are summarized in the project report. Parameters tuned include batch_size in [16, 32, 64] and epochs in [10, 20, 30, 40, 50, 100]. In view of the training and testing sample size, which are 1903 and 432 respectively, larger batch size was not used. Besides, the training and testing accuracy did not seem to improve much with epochs larger than 100. In below section, the best-performing hyperparameters tried are used for model training.

Long Short-Term Memory neural network (LSTM)¶

LSTM is another type of RNN model that has one additional gates compared to GRU. It is known to work well for longer sequences. Let's start with using 1 feature for model training.

In [96]:
# Define a function to build a LSTM Model
def buildLstmModel(dataShape):
    '''
    Parameters
    ----------
    dataShape: list
        the shape parameter of the training input
    Return
    ----------
    LSTM model
    '''
    N = dataShape[0]        # number of samples
    T = dataShape[1]        # timesteps
    D = dataShape[2]        # feature dimention
    K = 1                   # number of output

    model = Sequential()
    model.add(LSTM(50, return_sequences=True, input_shape=(T, D)))
    #model.add(Dropout(0.2))
    model.add(LSTM(50, return_sequences=False))
    #model.add(Dropout(0.2))
    model.add(Dense(K, activation='sigmoid' ))

    # Complie the model
    model.compile(optimizer='adam', loss='binary_crossentropy', metrics=['accuracy'])
    return model

LSTM with More Features¶

Hyperparameter turning has been done, details are summarized in the project report. Parameters tuned include batch_size in [16, 32, 64] and epochs in [10, 20, 30, 40, 50, 100]. In view of the training and testing sample size, which are 1903 and 432 respectively, larger batch size was not used. Besides, the training and testing accuracy did not seem to improve much with epochs larger than 100. Unlike GRU, whose training accuracy was capped at around 62%, LSTM achieved higher training accuracy of up to 88% with similar batch size and epoch settings. However, the testing accuracy for both models appeared comparable. In below section, the best-performing hyperparameters tried are used for model training.

Results and Conclusion¶

In this project, I used Random Forest, Gated Recurrent Unit(GRU) and Long Short Term Memory neural network(LSTM) along with time series stock data to build a classification model for predicting the direction of stock price movement for the next 1 day or 2 days, and benchmarked the prediction accuracy against the Naive Method. Some key observations:

  • Prediction accuracy of machine learning models for this specific problem is not higher than 60%.
  • Machine Learning models outperform the Naive Method by up to 7% higher test accuracy. However, this improvement is not significant compared to some of other machine learning classification use cases.
  • Prediction accuracy for 1-day ahead is up to 5% higher than for 2-day ahead.
  • LSTM which utilizes past sequence data appears to have the best performance among the models evaluated. However, longer timesteps do not significantly improve model performance.
  • Models trained using multiple features tend to but not always have higher prediction accuracy than those trained using a single feature.

Why is the accuracy of ML models not high in this specific case? One possible reason is that crucial factors that affect stock price movement are not captured in the available dataset used for model training. To name a few -- overnight news, unexpected events, politics, market sentiments, or even some celebrity posting a tweet -- these factors may not be quantified into the training data and used for model training in the previous day. On the other hand, if a model can easily predict the direction of stock price movement with publicly available data at high accuracy, such model would be exploited in a real investment or trading strategy and make a plenty of money. Meanwhile, majority of market participants might seek to adopt the same model whereby market dynamics could change again, making the models superior performance no longer hold.

Improvements¶

From data's perspective, adding and tracking additional metrics such as market events and events' impacts to the stock price, e.g. expected percentage contribution to the stock price change, impact factor on a scale of 0 to 10, etc, may be useful and likely to enable higher predictive power of machine learning models. Web scrapers can be used to retrieve market news and events for establishing such metrics. However, it may be challenging to restore and backfill these metrics for the past few decades and maintain such data as a private competitive edge. Alternative data sources that provide relevant information may also be explored. On the other hand, more technical indicators such as Bollinger Bands and standard deviation of stock price can be evaluated as additional features for any potential contribution to model performance.

From model training's perspective, if more time were given, some additional optimization can be done, such as cross-validation and further hyperparameter tuning. Besides, the models can be evaluated using more stock symbols to ensure consistency of model performance.
